http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A meaningful collection of concepts.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Uma ideia ou noção; uma unidade de pensamento.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: An idea or notion; a unit of thought.
An ordered collection of concepts, where both the grouping and the ordering are meaningful.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: Ordered collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed in a specific order, and optionally under a 'node label'.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The range of skos:altLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.
skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: An alternative lexical label for a resource.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: Acronyms, abbreviations, spelling variants, and irregular plural/singular forms may be included among the alternative labels for a concept. Mis-spelled terms are normally included as hidden labels (see skos:hiddenLabel).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Broader concepts are typically rendered as parents in a concept hierarchy (tree).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: skos:broaderTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:broader.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: By convention, skos:broaderTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A note about a modification to a concept.
A statement or formal explanation of the meaning of a concept.
A note for an editor, translator or maintainer of the vocabulary.
An example of the use of a concept.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The range of skos:hiddenLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.
skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A lexical label for a resource that should be hidden when generating visual displays of the resource, but should still be accessible to free text search operations.
A note about the past state/use/meaning of a concept.
Relates a collection to one of its members.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
For any resource, every item in the list given as the value of the
      skos:memberList property is also a value of the skos:member property.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Relates an ordered collection to the RDF list containing its members.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Narrower concepts are typically rendered as children in a concept hierarchy (tree).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: skos:narrowerTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:narrower.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: By convention, skos:narrowerTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A notation, also known as classification code, is a string of characters such as "T58.5" or "303.4833" used to uniquely identify a concept within the scope of a given concept scheme.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: By convention, skos:notation is used with a typed literal in the object position of the triple.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A general note, for any purpose.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: This property may be used directly, or as a super-property for more specific note types.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A resource has no more than one value of skos:prefLabel per language tag, and no more than one value of skos:prefLabel without language tag.
The range of skos:prefLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise
      disjoint properties.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The preferred lexical label for a resource, in a given language.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: skos:related is disjoint with skos:broaderTransitive

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Relates a concept to a concept with which there is an associative semantic relationship.
A note that helps to clarify the meaning and/or the use of a concept.
Links a concept to a concept related by meaning.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value: This property should not be used directly, but as a super-property for all properties denoting a relationship of meaning between concepts.
